<h2>The question</h2>
<p>
    <a href="/backlog/867-per-page-rollout-ratchet-for-the-we-docs-fui-dogfood/">#867</a> asks what is actually
    left of the &ldquo;per-page rollout ratchet&rdquo; for the WE-docs&#8594;FUI dogfood, and in what shape. The
    ratchet <em>infrastructure</em> is done: the rendered-site axe lane
    (<a href="/backlog/770-rendered-site-a11y-gate-axe-lane-route-allowlist-we-docs/">#770</a>, ratified by
    <a href="/backlog/763-gate-ui-best-practices-on-website-changes-rendered-site-a11y/">#763</a>) with a
    warn&#8594;enforce posture, ten routes flipped to build-blocking
    (<a href="/backlog/793-remediate-we-docs-a11y-violations-flip-the-rendered-site-gat/">#793</a>/<a href="/backlog/805-flip-backlog-rendered-site-a11y-route-to-enforce-once-backlo/">#805</a>),
    and the route set auto-derived from <code>/sitemap.xml</code> at scope-C
    (<a href="/backlog/774-auto-derive-the-a11y-gate-route-set-from-the-11ty-collection/">#774</a>,
    <a href="/backlog/847-a11y-gate-derives-route-set-from-sitemap-scope-c-sampling/">#847</a>), mirrored per-repo
    to the FUI site (#849). What was never designed is the ratchet <em>policy</em>: <strong>what does promotion
    track</strong> (measurement alone, or dogfood-conversion + measurement), and <strong>what is the endgame
    posture</strong> once the current route set is fully enforced?
</p>

